Cell.Data: The Clinical View functionality for Coding Settings in Rave enables users to specify full coding dictionary hierarchy in the clinical views. For example, a user can specify, the term, the code for the System Organ Class (SOC), and the high level term (HLT) from the MedDRA Coding Dictionary to show in the Clinical Views. If a suffix is specified, the corresponding column will appear in the clinical views.

Cell.ss:Data: TRUE = Break a form’s signature if a field was deleted on the target CRF version as a result of the migration. FALSE = Do not break the form's signature if a field was deleted. [Default: FALSE] Note: This global setting may be overridden by the user for a specific migration job run.

TRUE = Break a data point’s signature if the field label is changed in the target version. [Default: FALSE] FALSE = Do not break the data point's signature if the field label changed. Note: This global setting may be overridden by the user for a specific migration job run.

TRUE = Break a data point’s signature if a field is not associated with a data dictionary, and the data point value is changed as a result of migration. FALSE = Do not break the data point's signature if the data point value is changed for a non-dictionary field. [Default: FALSE] Note: This global setting may be overridden by the user for a specific migration job run.

TRUE = Break a data point’s signature if the data point is associated with a data dictionary entry prior to the migration, and the code for the dictionary entry is changed or re-mapped in the target version. FALSE = Do not break the data point's signature if the data dictionary entry is changed for the data point. [Default: FALSE] Note: This global setting may be overridden by the user for a specific migration job run.

TRUE = Break a data point’s signature if the data point is associated with a data dictionary entry prior to the migration, and the user string for the dictionary entry is changed or re-mapped in the target version. FALSE = Do not break a data point's signature if the user strin of it's data dictionary entry is changed. [Default: FALSE] Note: This global setting may be overridden by the user for a specific migration job run.

TRUE = Break a data point’s signature if the data point is associated with a unit dictionary and if the unit dictionary entry coded unit for the data point is changed in the target version. FALSE = Do not break a data point's signature if the coded unit of it's data dictionary entry is changed. [Default: FALSE] Note: This global setting may be overridden by the user for a specific migration job run.

TRUE = Break a data point’s signature if the data point is associated with a unit dictionary and if the unit dictionary entry user string for the data point is changed in the target version. FALSE = Do not break a data point's signature if the user string of it's unit dictionary entry is changed. [Default: FALSE] Note: This global setting may be overridden by the user for a specific migration job run.

TRUE = Break a data point’s signature if a field’s IsVisible property changes as a result of the migration. FALSE = Do not break a data point's signature if the field's visibility is changed. [Default: FALSE] Note: This global setting may be overridden by the user for a specific migration job run.

TRUE = Break a data point’s signature if a data point was conformant prior to migration, and is set to non-conformant as a result of the migration. FALSE = Do not break a data point's signature if the data point's conformancy is changed. [Default: FALSE] Note: This global setting may be overridden by the user for a specific migration job run.

Cell.ss:Data: Fill in the configuration data for the locales which will be used in your system. To configure each locale, set up the following: Locale Code - Enter the 3-leter language code for the locale. A list of all standard codes can be found on http://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/englangn.html#cd Based On - Enter an existing language on which you wish to base the new locale. The initial strings for the new locale will be copied from that language. Description - Enter description text for the locale. Help Folder - Specify the folder path, if any, which contains localized help for this locale. This folder path (e.g., Chinese\Mandarine) will have to exist in the Rave web server path under MedidataRAVE\Help in order for the users to view localized help. Submit on Enter - Select 'FALSE' to allow users to use the ENTER key as part of typing in text in Rave fields. This is required for data entry in certain asian languages. Select 'TRUE' to use the ENTER key for sumitting the screen. [Default: TRUE] Name Format - Specify which elements of the user name you want the system to display and in which order to display them. Use any of the following: * {FNAME} = First Name * {LNAME} = Last Name * {TITLE} = Title * {MNAME} = Middle Name * {SAL} = Salutation * {CRED} = Credentials Date Format - Specify the date format which will be displayed by Rave. Date/Time Format - Specify the date and time format which will be displayed by Rave whenever both date and time are used.

Cell.ss:Data: For Architect Projects, provide the following information: Role - the name of the Role which a user can be assigned for working with Projects Role Actions - a comma delimited list of action permissions the Role contains. Refer to the list of actions below.

B.U: Role Actions for Architect Projects Roles

ss:Data.Font: : permission to create a new Project
: permission to inactivate Projects
permission to view Projects
permission to modify Projects (implies Read permission)
: permission to update the following draft objects: Forms, Folders, Matrices, Data & Unit Dictionaries, and Lab Settings. (implies Read and Update permissions)
: permission to update the following draft objects: Edit Checks, Custom Functions and Derivations. (implies Read and Update permissions)
: permission to publish a draft to a version (implies Read permission)
: permission to push a draft version to auxiliary sites (implies Read permission)
: permission to push a draft version to production sites (implies Read permission)
: permission to define copy sources (other Projects or Global Library Volumes) for a Project
: permission to create a migration plan (implies Read permission)
: permission to execute a migration plan on auxiliary sites (implies Read permission)
: permission to execute a migration plan on production sites (implies Read permission)
: permission to download Project drafts into spreadsheets
: permission to upload a spreadsheet into a Project, and merge, replace, or create new drafts.
: permission to set up groups of draft objects as a proposal for inclusion in a Global Library Volume
: When checked, the system will allow the selected Role to lock a published CRF version. Having this permission implies a Publish permission.
: When checked, the system will allow the selected Role to unlock a published CRF version. Having this permission implies a Publish permission.
: When checked, the system will allow the selected Role to edit variables that are referenced by edit checks and derivations.
ss:Data.B: Set Does not participate in Signature
ss:Data.Font: : When checked, the system will allow a user with this role to set the Does not Participate in Signature flag for an EDC form field in Architect Form Designer.

Cell.ss:Data: Review Groups are set up to review specific data within the EDC module. Each Review Group has different review capabilities. Cell.ss:Data: Markings Groups enable markings, such as queries, to be directed to specific Roles. Cell.ss:Data: A Role in Rave is a set of User Permissions, given to a user for a specific Study. The permissions allow the user to perform certain Actions. These Actions can be further restricted by different Pre-conditions. To define a Role, set up the following: Name - Enter the Role name Active - Select 'TRUE' to make the Role active and available for use. Select 'FALSE' to inactivate a Role. Change Codes - List all the Change Codes which will be available for the user, separated by a comma (see list in Change Codes worksheet)Permissions - List the Permissions given to a user for this Role. Separate each permission by a comma. (see list below)Subject Status - Select one or more Subject Statuses which a user with this Role will be allowed to view. Note: At least 1 Subject Status MUST be selected. Separate the list with commas (see list in Subject Status worksheet)Note: The Permission 'View Subject With Any Status' implies that all Subject Statues are allowed.

The following Role permissions define what a particular Role can do within the EDC module: Can Batch Sign: Allows users with this role to sign multiple forms requiring electronic signatures from the subject calendar. Can Inactivate Form: Allows users with this role to only inactivate forms for subjects they have access to within the form itself. Can Modify Templates: Allows users with this role to change the fields on whichever templates are being used for forms within the EDC module. Note: The field must be set as template fields in the Architect module.

Cell.ss:Data: During a study, data may not always be available for entry into all required fields. When this occurs, a user who belongs to a Role that has been configured for Missing Codes can enter a valid code for the missing data. This missing code will replace the actual data value to indicate that the field was left empty on purpose. To set up a Missing Code for a Role, fill in: Role - Select the Role for which the Missing Code is valid Missing Code - Enter the text which will serve to indicate a missing code Description - Enter a description of the Missing Code Active - Select 'TRUE' to make the Missing Code avaialble for use, or 'FALSE' to remove it from the avaialble list of Missing Codes

A user with Role permission 'Can Inactivate Form' or 'Can Reactivate Form' can inactivate/reactivate any form for a subject (except for Primary Form). When activating/inactivating a form, the system prompts the user to select a Reason Code for the activation/inactivation. The list of Reason Codes is configured per Role. To configure Reason Codes, set up the following: Role - Select the Role for which the Reason Code is valid Reason Code - Enter the text which will be used as a Reason Code Description - Enter a description of the Reason Code Reason Type - Select whether the Reason Code should be used for activations of inactivations Active - Select 'TRUE' to make the Reason Code avaialble for use, or 'FALSE' to remove it from the avaialble list of Reason Codes

Role Actions define the action which a specific Role is allowed to perform. To configure the Role Actions, set up the following: Role - Select the desired Role in the Role column (Roles are defined on the Roles worksheet) Role Action - List the Role Actions assigned to the selected Role. Separate each permission by a delimiter (e.g., comma). (see explanations below) (PreCondition-STATUS) - List pairs of pre-conditions and their status for each Role Action in parenthesis, following the action. Each pre-condition should be followed by it's Status. Set status to TRUE if the pre-condition should be true for permission to be granted. Set it to FALSE if the pre-condition should NOT be true for permission to be granted. E.g., Freeze(IsReviewed=TRUE, RequiresCoding=FALSE) Note: A pre-condition needs to be on the list in order to take effect. i.e., empty pre-condition lists imply no pre-conditions.
